<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="454" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1573,1958]" pageId="3" pageNumber="454">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1573,1598]" pageId="3" pageNumber="454">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male. In the group IV key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier" box="[614,818,1573,1598]" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1964) Revision of the North American phorid flies. Part II. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Aphiochaeta. Studia Entomologica, 7, 257 - 416." type="journal article" year="1964">
Borgmeier (
<number box="[750,810,1573,1598]" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" value="1964.0">1964</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[830,941,1573,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bradyi">
<emphasis box="[830,941,1573,1597]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="454">M. bradyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
keys to couplet 
<number box="[1127,1155,1574,1598]" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" value="17.0">17</number>
but differs from both 
<taxonomicName authority="Malloch" authorityName="Malloch" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dificilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="454">M. dificilis</emphasis>
Malloch
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" box="[371,621,1609,1634]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cribella">
<emphasis box="[371,495,1609,1633]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="454">M. cribella</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
by having a characteristic basal fringe of 
<number box="[1088,1116,1610,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" value="12.0">12</number>
+ robust, curved setae on the hind femur (F 
<number box="[309,323,1646,1670]" pageId="3" pageNumber="454" value="3.0">3</number>
), which those species lack.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
